{
  "What is the formula for density?": "",
  "Density = Volume ÷ Mass": "",
  "Density = Mass ÷ Volume": "",
  "Density = Mass × Volume": "",
  "Density = Mass + Volume": "",
  "Density is calculated by dividing mass by volume: D = M ÷ V. This tells you how much matter is packed into a given amount of space.": "",
  "What is the standard unit for density in the metric system?": "",
  "grams per liter (g/L)": "",
  "grams per cubic centimeter (g/cm³)": "",
  "kilograms per meter (kg/m)": "",
  "milliliters per gram (mL/g)": "",
  "The standard unit for density is grams per cubic centimeter (g/cm³) for solids and grams per milliliter (g/mL) for liquids. Since 1 cm³ = 1 mL, these units are equivalent.": "",
  "What is the density of pure water at room temperature?": "",
  "10 g/cm³": "",
  "0.1 g/cm³": "",
  "1.0 g/cm³": "",
  "100 g/cm³": "",
  "Pure water has a density of approximately 1.0 g/cm³ (or 1.0 g/mL) at room temperature. This value is useful as a reference — objects denser than 1.0 g/cm³ sink in water, and less dense objects float.": "",
  "An object has a mass of 30 g and a volume of 10 cm³. What is its density?": "",
  "300 g/cm³": "",
  "3 g/cm³": "",
  "0.33 g/cm³": "",
  "20 g/cm³": "",
  "Density = Mass ÷ Volume = 30 g ÷ 10 cm³ = 3 g/cm³. This object is denser than water (1.0 g/cm³), so it would sink.": "",
  "If an object is less dense than water, what will it do when placed in water?": "",
  "Sink to the bottom": "",
  "Float on the surface": "",
  "Dissolve completely": "",
  "Stay in the middle": "",
  "Objects less dense than water (density < 1.0 g/cm³) float. Objects more dense than water (density > 1.0 g/cm³) sink. This is why wood floats and metal sinks.": "",
  "How do you find the volume of a rectangular solid (box)?": "",
  "Length + Width + Height": "",
  "Length × Width × Height": "",
  "Length × Width only": "",
  "2 × (Length + Width)": "",
  "The volume of a rectangular solid is calculated by multiplying Length × Width × Height. For example, a box that is 5 cm × 3 cm × 2 cm has a volume of 30 cm³.": "",
  "How do you measure the volume of an irregularly shaped object like a rock?": "",
  "Measure its length, width, and height with a ruler and multiply": "",
  "Use the water displacement method in a graduated cylinder": "",
  "Weigh it on a balance and convert the mass to volume directly": "",
  "Estimate its volume by comparing it to a known regular shape": "",
  "Water displacement works by submerging the object in water and measuring the volume of water it pushes aside. The difference between the water level before and after equals the object's volume.": "",
  "A graduated cylinder contains 50 mL of water. After a rock is added, the water level rises to 65 mL. What is the volume of the rock?": "",
  "65 mL": "",
  "50 mL": "",
  "15 mL": "",
  "115 mL": "",
  "The volume of the rock equals the water displaced: 65 mL − 50 mL = 15 mL (or 15 cm³, since 1 mL = 1 cm³). The rock pushed the water up by 15 mL.": "",
  "Which object is the most dense?": "",
  "A wooden block: 10 g, 20 cm³": "",
  "A metal cube: 40 g, 5 cm³": "",
  "A plastic ball: 15 g, 25 cm³": "",
  "A foam block: 5 g, 50 cm³": "",
